    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-07-03T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-07-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="1078"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1078">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 341.622a/12</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">
                        <persName type="from">Goulder, White and Garry</persName> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cleveland, Ohio</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-07-03">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 3, 1915</hi>.</date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 11.30 a. m.</hi>] </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>On June 30 we sent to Solicitor of State Department account of interference with
                    seamen on American ship <hi rend="italic">Niagara</hi> in Canadian. Canal at
                    Port Colborne,<note n="1" xml:id="d1078fn1">Not printed.</note> at the same time
                    we wrote Canadian Minister of War. There has been no reply. Another case has
                    occurred with the steamship <hi rend="italic">Lackawanna</hi>. May we not have
                    consideration and reply?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Goulder, White, and Garry</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
